{"timestamp": "2026-05-28 12:22:49,290", "level": "INFO", "logger": "flow.validation", "module": "logging_config", "function": "log_validation_result", "line": 185, "message": "{\"timestamp\": \"2026-05-28T12:22:49.290678\", \"task_id\": \"unknown\", \"task_objective\": \"Conduct the technical interview using prepared questions aligned to the job description and resume insights.\", \"result\": \"```text\\n1. Analyze Job Description\\n   - Skills: Python, SQL, Spark, AWS (S3, Lambda, EMR), Azure Databricks, data modeling, ETL, data warehousing.\\n   - Experience: 5+ years, Bachelor's in CS or related.\\n   - Responsibilities: Data pipelines, ML model operationalization, data quality, mentoring.\\n\\n2. Analyze Candidate Resume\\n   - Experience: Java, Spring Boot, microservices, REST APIs, AWS (EC2, S3, RDS), Docker, Kubernetes.\\n   - Skills: Java, Python, SQL, Spring Boot, AWS, Docker, Kubernetes.\\n   ...\", \"validation_type\": \"text\", \"status\": \"completed\", \"feedback\": \"here are some feedbacks:\\n- The current output for Step 3 only lists the questions; it does not actually “conduct” the interview (i.e., interviewer-candidate dialogue and candidate responses).\\n- To fulfill the requirement, you need a mock interview transcript showing both questions and candidate answers, demonstrating alignment to the job description and resume.\\n- Keep the format as plain text and focus solely on Step 3.\\n\\nhere are the changes:\\n3. Conduct Technical Interview  \\nInterviewer: Thank you for joining today. Let’s dive in.\\n\\nQuestion 1:  \\nInterviewer: “Given a dataset with missing values, what strategies would you use for imputation, and how would you evaluate their effectiveness?”  \\nCandidate: “First, I’d profile the data in Python/Pandas to see the missing patterns. For numerical features, I might use mean or median imputation, or predictive imputation with K-Nearest Neighbors if relationships exist. For time series, I could use forward or backward fill. For categoricals, I’d use the mode or create a ‘Missing’ category. To evaluate, I’d hold out a subset with artificial missing values, impute, and compare RMSE or classification accuracy against the ground truth.”\\n\\nInterviewer (follow-up): “How would you implement KNN imputation at scale on Spark?”  \\nCandidate: “In Spark, I’d use the MLlib KNN model or convert data to RDD of vectors and apply a broadcast KNN algorithm. Alternatively, I’d pivot to Databricks notebooks and leverage built-in imputation functions or run a scalable cross-validator with VectorAssembler and KNN library.”\\n\\nQuestion 2:  \\nInterviewer: “Describe a time you had to optimize a slow-running data pipeline. What tools and techniques did you use?”  \\nCandidate: “On my last project, a daily Spark job on EMR was taking 3 hours. I first used the Spark UI to identify skewed joins. I added salting to balance partitions, cached intermediate DataFrames to avoid recomputation, and switched from Python UDFs to native Spark SQL functions. I also tuned executor memory and parallelism. The runtime dropped to 45 minutes.”\\n\\nQuestion 3:  \\nInterviewer: “Explain the differences between a star schema and a snowflake schema in data warehousing. When would you choose one over the other?”  \\nCandidate: “A star schema has denormalized dimension tables directly linked to the fact table—simpler joins and faster query performance. A snowflake schema normalizes dimensions, which reduces redundancy and storage but adds join complexity. For a high-performance BI use case on Azure Databricks with large data volumes, I’d pick star. If storage cost or data integrity is critical, I’d use snowflake.”\\n\\nQuestion 4:  \\nInterviewer: “How do you ensure data quality and consistency in your ETL pipelines?”  \\nCandidate: “I implement validation checks at each stage—schema enforcement via AWS Glue Catalog, null and range checks in Spark, and record counts. I build automated alerts in Lambda functions that trigger if thresholds fail, and I store audit logs in S3. Finally, I run unit tests in a CI/CD pipeline before deployment.”\\n\\nQuestion 5:  \\nInterviewer: “Walk me through setting up a new AWS Lambda function to process data from an S3 bucket.”  \\nCandidate: “First, create the Lambda in AWS Console or via Terraform, assign an IAM role with S3 read permissions. Next, configure an S3 event notification to invoke the function on object creation. In the function code (Python), I’d use boto3 to fetch the file, process it—e.g., parse CSV or trigger a Glue job—then write results back to another S3 path. I’d also set up CloudWatch logs and adjust memory/timeout based on payload size.”\"}"}
